metadata.name: "A"
metadata.description:
Mikhail Molochnikov is the author of the Alphabet collection. The artist's paintings are kept in the collections of the State Russian Museum, the Tretyakov Gallery, the Pushkin Museum, museums in the USA, Germany, Switzerland and other countries now.

The collection includes 33 letters of the Russian Alphabet. Each symbol is represented in motion with the accompaniment of music by the famous Russian composer Anton Rubinstein.
The letter "A" is the first symbol not only of the Russian alphabet, but also of all alphabets based on Cyrillic. The letter "A" appeared as a pictogram of the word "Aleph" ("bull") in 1700 BC. The symbol "A" is the genesis of the entire collection. It is the beginning of the Alphabet's entry into the meta-universe. The first owner of the symbol will go down in history.

The symbol can be collected by people whose names begin with the letter "A". And also, those for whom the words to this letter have a certain meaning: absolute, abstraction, army, angel, aristocra
